[1] New Zealand
[2] Italy

******
[1] New Zealand
Date: 12 Aug 2011
Source: New Zealand Herald [edited]
http://www.nzherald.co.nz/health/news/article.cfm?c_id=204&objectid=10744647


Kiwifruit [bacterial canker caused by strain] Psa V is taking a firmer
grip, and its spread is more aggressive than expected, the industry
reported. The disease has continued to spread throughout the Te Puke
region in the Bay of Plenty and into new areas. It has now been found
in the Matapihi area, on the outskirts of Tauranga.

"This is seen to be a significant deterioration in the situation, with
spread of the disease outside the previously affected geographic
areas," Seeka Kiwifruit Industries said. Generally across the
industry, detections have increased. A total of 170 orchards have now
been affected across a wide area.

The gold kiwifruit variety continues to be particularly susceptible,
and orchards are generally severely affected, while secondary
infections have been seen in the green variety in only a small number
of cases, with orchards showing only light symptoms. "The spread over
the winter months has been more aggressive than expected," Seeka
said.

The disease has been seen in orchards covering 200 ha of green and 138
ha of gold kiwifruit. In one orchard covering 15.8 ha of gold and 5.57
ha of green, the infected plants have been removed, and there has been
no evidence of further infection to date. In another orchard covering
16.6 ha of gold, efforts to contain the infection have not been
successful. Growers have formed a taskforce to search for a scientific
solution to fight Psa V.

--
