******
[2] Italy
Date: June 2011
Source: Source: European Plant Protection Organisation (EPPO)
Reporting Service 6/2011/131 [edited]
http://archives.eppo.org/EPPOReporting/2011/Rse-1106.pdf


In 2011, _Pseudomonas syringae_ pv. _actinidiae_ (EPPO Alert List)
continued to spread in Italy and was detected for the 1st time in the
following regions:

- Calabria, in some plants of _Actinidia chinensis_ grown in an
orchard in the municipality of Rosarno (Province of Reggio Calabria).
- Campania, in plants of _A. deliciosa_ cv. "Jin Tao." These plants
had been planted in 2010, and the orchard was located in the
municipality of Sessa Auruca (Province of Caserta).
- Friuli-Venezia Giulia, in 4 young orchards of _A. deliciosa_ cv.
"Hayward" located in the municipalities of Bertiolo, Camino al
Tagliamento and Codroipo (province of Udine) and in the greenhouse of
a nursery located in the municipality of Sacile (Province of
Pordenone).

In all regions, emergency measures have been taken to control or
eradicate the bacterial canker of kiwifruit in accordance with the
Italian Ministerial decree of February 2011.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Bacterial canker of kiwifruit (_Actinidia_ species and hybrids)
caused by _Pseudomonas syringae_ pv. _actinidiae_ was originally
described in Japan in 1989, but its area of origin is uncertain.
Symptoms include discolouration of buds and vascular tissues, leaf
spots, wilting, stem and twig cankers with characteristic red exudate,
fruit collapse, and eventually death of the plant. The disease is
favoured by cool temperatures and high humidity, thus symptoms are
usually seen in spring and autumn.

Data on epidemiology are still lacking, but infection is thought to
occur via natural leaf openings and wounds. The pathogen is suspected
to be spread by heavy rain, strong winds, mechanical means (including
animal and human activities), and infected planting material. Spread
with infected fruit and/or pollen cannot be excluded until conclusive
data become available.

Generally, disease management of bacterial diseases may include
cultural practices, crop rotation, phytosanitation to prevent spread,
use of clean planting material and resistant crop varieties, but
specific control strategies for kiwi canker are being developed.
Chemical control (copper compounds, antibiotics) is used in Japan, but
resistant pathogen strains have emerged.

A recent outbreak in Italy (ProMED-mail post 20100414.1207) affecting
25 percent of the Zespri Gold variety vines was found to be due to the
emergence of a new, very virulent strain, Psa V. In New Zealand, 2
separate pathogen strains have been identified including the virulent
Psa V.

